e Aukhiyas and the Kha _n_ _d_ ikiyas; the \xc3\x82pastambins are a\nsubdivision of the latter branch. We have also the list of the contents\n(anakrama _n_ i) of the \xc3\x82treyas, a subdivision of the Aukhiyas.\n\n[xxvii:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_36) It has come down to us in two different\nrecensions, the Aitareya and the Kaushitaki (or _S_ a\xe1\xb9\x85khayana) Brahma _n_ a.\n\n[xxvii:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_37) Professor Weber, however, thinks there may be\nsome reason for this derivation; the name of Taittiriya having perhaps been\napplied to this school on account of the motley (partridge-like) character of\nits texts. According to the story alluded to, Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya, having been\ntaught the old Ya _g_ us texts by Vai _s_ ampayana, incurred the displeasure\nof his teacher, and was forced by him to disgorge the sacred science which, on\nfalling to the ground, became soiled p. xxviii (hence Black Ya _g_ us), and\nwas picked up by Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya's condisciples, who had assumed the form\nof partridges. This story seems first to occur in the Pura _n_ as; see\nWilson's translation of the Vish _n_ u Pura _n_ a (ed. Hall), III, p. 54. Pa\n_n_ ini (IV, 3, 102) and Pata _\xc3\xb1_ _g_ ali only know of the Taittiriya texts as\n'promulgated by Tittiri.'\n\n[xxviii:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_38) Zeitsch. der D. M. G., IV, p. 289 seq.;\nreprinted in Indische Streifen I, p. 31 seq.\n\n[xxix:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_39) The Ka _n_ va text is divided into seventeen\nbooks. Ka _n_ _d_ as 12-15 correspond to Madhyandina 10-13; and ka _n_ _d_ a\n16, which treats [of](errata.htm#2) the Pravargya ceremony, corresponds to the\nfirst three adhyayas of the last ka _n_ _d_ a of the Madhyandinas. Thus, in\nthe Ka _n_ va recension the fourteenth ka _n_ _d_ a, called 'madhyama,' is the\nmiddle one of ka _n_ _d_ as 12-16; the seventeenth ka _n_ _d_ a, or B _ri_\nhadara _n_ yaka, being apparently considered as a supplement. Perhaps this\ndivision is more original than that of the Madhyandinas.\n\n[xxx:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_40) The accuracy of this list cannot he relied upon, as\nseveral mistakes occur in the number of ka _n_ _d_ ikas there given. It is,\nhowever, unlikely that the scribe should have committed any mistake regarding\nthe number of adhyayas.\n\n[xxx:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_41) Literally 'together with the rahasya (sarahasyam),'\n&c.\n\n[xxx:3](sbe1202.htm#fr_42) History of Indian Literature, p. 507 seq.\n\n[xxxi:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_43) See, however, _S_ at. Br. II, 5, 1, 2-3, where Ya\n_g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya's opinion is referred to as being contrary to the Rig-veda.\n\n[xxxi:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_44) See Weber, Ind. Stud. XIII, p. 266 seq.\n\n[xxxii:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_45) The author of this passage would seem to imply,\nthough he does not exactly express it, that this was the first fire-altar\nbuilt in the proper way.\n\n[xxxiii:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_46) I here give, side by side, the lists, in\ninverted order, from Sa _m_ _g_ ivi-putra upwards. For the complete lists, see\nMax Muller, History of Ancient Sanskrit Literature, p. 438 seq.\n\nEnd of Book XIV.\n\n|\n\nEnd of Book X.  \n  \n---|---  \n  \n58\\. \xc3\x82ditya.\n\n|\n\n(52) Brahman Svayambhu.  \n  \n57\\. Ambi _n_ i.\n\n|\n\n  \n  \n56\\. Va _k_.\n\n|\n\n(51) Pra _g_ apati.  \n  \n55\\. Ka _s_ yapa Naidhruvi.\n\n|\n\n  \n  \n54\\. _S_ ilpa Ka _s_ yapa.\n\n|\n\n  \n  \n53\\. Harita Ka _s_ yapa.\n\n|\n\n(50) Tura Kavasheya.  \n  \n52\\. Asita Varshaga _n_ a.\n\n|\n\n  \n  \n51\\. _G_ ihvavat Badhyoga.\n\n|\n\n(49) Va _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ ava _k_ as Ra _g_ astambayana.  \n  \n50\\. Va _g_ a _s_ ravas.\n\n|\n\n  \n  \n49\\. Ku _s_ ri.\n\n|\n\n(48) Ku _s_ ri.  \n  \n48\\. Upave _s_ i.\n\n|\n\n(47) _S_ a _n_ _d_ ilya.  \n  \n47\\. Aru _n_ a.\n\n|\n\n  \n  \n46\\. Uddalaka (\xc3\x82ru _n_ eya).\n\n|\n\n(46) Vatsya.  \n  \n45\\. Ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ avalkya (Va _g_ asaneya).\n\n|\n\n(45) Vamakakshaya _n_ a.  \n  \n44, \xc3\x82suri.\n\n|\n\n(44) Mahitthi.  \n  \n43\\. Asuraya _n_ a.\n\n|\n\n(43) Kautsa.  \n  \n42\\. Pra 