) See Ludwig, Rig-veda III, p. 205; Zimmer,\nAltindisches Leben, p. 103.\n\n[xlii:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_68) The passage III, 2, 3, 15, where the Kuru-Pa _\xc3\xb1_\n_k_ alas are apparently placed in the north--in direct contradiction to XI, 4,\n1, 1, where they are placed in opposition to the Northerners (udi _k_ ya _h_\n)--seems to go against this supposition. Professor Weber, Ind. Stud. I, 191,\ntries to get over this difficulty by translating Kurupa _\xc3\xb1_ _k_ alatra by 'as\namong the Kuru-Pa _\xc3\xb1_ _k_ alas,' instead of among the Kuru-Pa _\xc3\xb1_ _k_ alas;'\nso that the meaning of the passage would be that 'the same language is spoken\nin the northern region, as among the Kuru-Pa _\xc3\xb1_ _k_ alas.' Unfortunately,\nhowever, the Ka _n_ va text of the passage is not favourable to this\ninterpretation. It runs as follows (K. IV. a, 3, 10):--udi _k_ im pathyaya\nsvastya vag vai pathya svastis tasmad atrottarahai vag vadatityahu _h_ kurupa\n_\xc3\xb1_ _k_ aleshu kurumahavisheshv ity eta _m_ hi taya di _s_ a _m_ pra _g_ anann\nesha hi tasya dik pra _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ ata.\n\n[xlii:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_69) He is styled ra _g_ anyabandhu in _Kh_ andogyop.\nV, 3, 5.\n\n[xliii:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_70) They occupied the country about the modern\nBenares (Ka _s_ i).\n\n[xliii:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_71) Dh _ri_ tarash _t_ ra Vai _k_ itravirya, whose\nsons and nephews form the chief parties of this great feud, is mentioned in\nthe Ka _th_ aka 10, 6. From this passage--which, unfortunately, is not in a\nvery good condition in the Berlin MS.--it would appear that animosities had\nthen existed between the Kurus and Pa _\xc3\xb1_ _k_ alas. It is doubtful, however,\nwhether this part of the Ka _th_ aka is older than the bulk of the _S_\natapatha. See Weber, Ind. Stud. III, 469 seq.\n\n[xliii:3](sbe1202.htm#fr_72) See Weber, Ind. Stud. I, 176.\n\n[xliv:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_73) Viz. ka _n_ _d_ as 4-7, 9, 10, 12, 14-17.\n\n[xliv:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_74) For instance, the brahma _n_ as Madhy. I, 4, 3;\nII, 3, 2 and 3; IV, 5, 10; 6, 8 are wanting in the Oxford MS.; see p. 338,\nnote 3.--In the fourth (fifth Ka _n_ va) ka _n_ _d_ a, the Ka _n_ vas, on the\nother hand, have two brahma _n_ as (V, 7, 5; 8, 2, the latter of which treats\nof the adabhya graha, Va _g_. S. VIII, 99-50) which are not found in the\nMadhyandina text.\n\n[xlv:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_75) Professor Weber thinks that the sutra of Vai _g_\navapa, of which mention is occasionally made in the commentaries on the\nKatiya-sutra, may belong to the White Ya _g_ us. See History of Indian\nLiterature, p. 142. Professor Buhler, Sacred Laws, I, p. xxvi, remarks that\n'Ka _n_ va is considered the author of the still existing Kalpa-sutras of the\nKa _n_ va school;' but I have found no notice of these sutras anywhere.\n\n[xlv:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_76) That is, in those adhyayas to which the Brahma _n_\na forms a running commentary.\n\n[xlv:3](sbe1202.htm#fr_77) I have not met with any exception in the ka _n_ _d_\nas hitherto examined.\n\n[xlv:4](sbe1202.htm#fr_78) See Aufrecht, Ait. Br. p. 418.\n\n[xlv:5](sbe1202.htm#fr_79) See also the form 'dheno _h_ ' mentioned above.\n\n[xlvi:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_80) Another curious feature of the Ka _n_ va text is\nthe frequent insertion of an 'ity uva _k_ a' in the middle of speeches, much\nlike the colloquial 'says he.' As an instance I may adduce K. IV, 2, 3, 3 (M.\nIII, 2, 3, 5):--Sa hova _k_ a 'ham eva vo ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ am amumuham iti hova _k_\na yad eva mayi tanvana iti ma _m_ ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ ad antaragata tenaiva vo ya _g_\n_\xc3\xb1_ am amumuham iti to mahya _m_ nu bhaga _m_ kalpayatety atha vo ya _g_ _\xc3\xb1_ a\n_h_ praro _k_ ishyata hi tatheti ho _k_ us, &c. The Ka _n_ vas also invert\nmuch more frequently an 'iti' in the middle of speeches.\n\n[xlvii:1](sbe1202.htm#fr_81) Das Altindische Neu- and Vollmondsopfer, p. xv.\n\n[xlvii:2](sbe1202.htm#fr_82) See, for instance, _S_ at. Br. I, 3, 1, 7; 8, 1,\n14.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: I, 1, 1. First Adhyaya. First Brahma _